codes.biscuit.skyblocklib.parsers

Class ActionBarParser

  • java.lang.Object
    • codes.biscuit.skyblocklib.parsers.ActionBarParser

  • public class ActionBarParser
extends java.lang.Object
    This class is used to parse action bar messages and get stats and other info out of them. Parsed info is always kept up-to-date elsewhere in SkyblockLib, like the SkyblockPlayer, but it can be customized whether that information should still be displayed in the action bar. Here is a list of currently parsed information:
    • Health and maximum health
    • Mana and maximum mana
    • Defense
    • Skill progress
    • Item charges/tickers

    In general, the action bar is divided into sections separated by 3 or more spaces (usually 5, zombie tickers by 4 , race timer by 12, trials of fire by 3). Examples can be found below. These sections get parsed individually and can be removed from the displayed action bar individually.

    By default, SkyblockLib will read info from the action bar, but not remove the text. To do so, you can affect what stays displayed by setting consumers on specific action bar sections or on every section, the so called general consumer. Consumers are ran after parsing is done, so if you require the parsed information it will already be available wherever it's stored. They determine how the consumed section should be displayed in the action bar, so setting it do display as null removes it. The easiest way to remove action bar text for a specific section, the health section for example, is to use the ActionBarConsumer.REMOVE_TEXT_CONSUMER by calling setHealthConsumer(ActionBarConsumer) with it.

    The general consumer is ran after every thing else, on every single section. So you can remove the entire action bar by simply setting ActionBarConsumer.REMOVE_TEXT_CONSUMER as the general consumer. Or you can run your own checks to cover sections that aren't handled by SkyblockLib by default.
    See the documentation for the consumer-setters for more detailed information what their sections look like.

    See the ActionBarConsumer documentation for more detailed information on how exactly to use one!

    Here are some example action bars:

    Normal: §c1390/1390❤ §a720§a❈ Defense §b183/171✎ Mana§r
    Normal with Skill XP: §c1390/1390❤ §3+10.9 Combat (313,937.1/600,000) §b183/171✎ Mana§r
    Zombie Sword: §c1390/1390❤ §a725§a❈ Defense §b175/233✎ Mana §a§lⓩⓩⓩⓩ§2§l§r
    Zombie Sword with Skill XP: §c1390/1390❤ §3+10.9 Combat (313,948/600,000) §b187/233✎ Mana §a§lⓩⓩⓩⓩ§2§l§r
    Normal with Wand: §c1390/1390❤+§c30▅ §a724§a❈ Defense §b97/171✎ Mana§r

    • Method Detail

      • parseActionBar

        public java.lang.String parseActionBar(java.lang.String actionBar)

        This should not be called outside SkyblockLib!

        Parses the stats out of an action bar message and returns a new action bar message without the parsed stats to display instead. Looks for Health, Defense, Mana, Skill XP and parses and uses the stats accordingly. Only removes the stats from the new action bar when consumed.
        Parameters:
        actionBar - Formatted action bar message
        Returns:
        New action bar without parsed stats.

      • setHealthConsumer

        public void setHealthConsumer(ActionBarConsumer healthConsumer)
        Sets the consumer on the health section. This section looks like this:

        §c1390/1390❤

        or like this:

        §c1390/1390❤+§c30▅

        if a healing wand is active. The parsed information is available as SkyblockPlayer.getHealth(), SkyblockPlayer.getMaxHealth() and SkyblockPlayer.getWandHealing().

        Set to null to remove

        Parameters:
        healthConsumer - The consumer

      • setChargesConsumer

        public void setChargesConsumer(ActionBarConsumer chargesConsumer)
        Sets the consumer on the charges section. This means the charges for the Zombie Sword or the tickers for the Scorpion foil. This section can have multiple shapes:

        Zombie with full charges: §a§lⓩⓩⓩⓩ§2§l§r

        Zombie with one used charges: §a§lⓩⓩⓩ§2§lⓄ§r

        Scorpion tickers: §e§lⓄⓄⓄⓄ§7§l§r

        Ornate: §e§lⓩⓩⓩ§6§lⓄⓄ§r

        Important to note here is that Zombie uses ⓩ with color code a for usable charges and Ⓞ with color code 2 for unusable charges.
        Scorpion uses Ⓞ with color code e for usable tickers, Ⓞ with color code 7 for unusable charges.
        Ornate uses ⓩ with color code e for usable charges, Ⓞ with color code 6 for unusable.
        The parsed information is available as SkyblockPlayer.getCurrentItemCharges().

        Set to null to remove

        Parameters:
        chargesConsumer - The consumer
